{"key":"post-13375179","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13375179</id>\n<content>Why are you guys worried about humidity in a shotgun terrarium?&amp;nbsp; Don't run a fan in the room with a shotgun.&amp;nbsp; It will disturb the natural air currents and impede proper operation.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Ok so right now im working with a 26 gallon shotgun FC with perlite and misting for humidity&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No, you're misting to replace the moisture which evaporates out of the cakes. This evaporation is the number one pinning trigger.&amp;nbsp; The perlite supplies humidity and the holes on all six sides supply fresh air.&amp;nbsp; If you run a fan or pipe in a humidifier, you run the risk of upsetting the natural balance, and either flooding or drying out your terrarium, both of which will reduce performance.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13375870</next>\n<prev>13375038</prev>\n<first>13374546</first>\n<last>13378958</last>\n<when>1287843921</when>\n<utime>10/23/10 05:25 PM</utime>\n</post>"}